<subSubSection id="85FBFA80D61028091D19FC8CE1AFFB9B" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61028091D19FC8CE13CFCA9" blockId="14.[567,781,804,830]" box="[567,781,804,830]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<heading id="96161E67D61028091D19FC8CE13CFCA9" allCaps="true" box="[567,781,804,830]" centered="true" fontSize="36" level="1" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" reason="1">
“ 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091D11FC8CE135FCA9" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[575,772,804,830]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">XENODONTINAE</taxonomicName>
”
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61028091F85FCF5E1AFFB9B" blockId="14.[114,1234,860,1297]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
More than a quarter century ago investigators began to realize that New World “xenodontine” snakes comprise two geographically overlapping clades—the Central American “xenodontines” and the South American “xenodontines”—as documented primarily by microcomplement fixation studies of serum albumins (
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091C31FC64E62AFC71" author="Dowling, Herndon G. &amp; Richard Highton &amp; George C. Maha &amp; Linda R. Maxson" box="[799,1051,972,999]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="309 - 329" refId="ref16076" refString="Dowling, Herndon G., Richard Highton, George C. Maha, and Linda R. Maxson. 1983. Biochemical evaluation of colubrid snake phylogeny. Journal of Zoology (London) 201 (3): 309 - 329." type="journal article" year="1983">Dowling et al., 1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091B05FC64E6FBFC71" author="Cadle, John E." box="[1067,1226,972,998]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="8 - 20" refId="ref15438" refString="Cadle, John E. 1984 a. Molecular systematics of Neotropical xenodontine snakes: I. South American xenodontines. Herpetologica 40 (1): 8 - 20." type="journal article" year="1984">Cadle, 1984a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091F56FC59E2F3FB9C" author="Cadle, John E." box="[120,194,1009,1035]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="21 - 30" refId="ref15469" refString="Cadle, John E. 1984 b. Molecular systematics of Neotropical xenodontine snakes: II. Central American xenodontines. Herpetologica 40 (1): 21 - 30." type="journal article" year="1984">1984b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091FE3FC5AE325FB9B" author="Cadle, John E." box="[205,276,1010,1036]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="641 - 652" refId="ref15500" refString="Cadle, John E. 1984 c. Molecular systematics of Neotropical xenodontine snakes: III. Overview of xenodontine phylogeny and the history of New World snakes. Copeia 1984 (3): 641 - 652." type="journal article" year="1984">1984c</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091E0FFC59E36CFB9B" author="Cadle, John E." box="[289,349,1009,1036]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref15539" refString="Cadle, John E. 1985. The Neotropical colubrid snake fauna (Serpentes: Colubridae): lineage components and biogeography. Systematic Zoology 34 (1): 1 - 20." type="journal article" year="1985">1985</bibRefCitation>
); for summary discussion see Zaher (1999: 5–7).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="85FBFA80D61028171F87FBBFE0DDFB74" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="17" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61028091F87FBBFE0FBFA86" blockId="14.[114,1234,860,1297]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
The predominantly Central American assemblage was recognized as subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091B6DFBBFE6F9FBA6" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[1091,1224,1047,1073]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadinae</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091F8CFB94E3E9FBC1" author="Dowling, Herndon G. &amp; Richard Highton &amp; George C. Maha &amp; Linda R. Maxson" box="[162,472,1084,1111]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="309 - 329" refId="ref16076" refString="Dowling, Herndon G., Richard Highton, George C. Maha, and Linda R. Maxson. 1983. Biochemical evaluation of colubrid snake phylogeny. Journal of Zoology (London) 201 (3): 309 - 329." type="journal article" year="1983">Dowling et al. (1983: 323</bibRefCitation>
, 326). Zaher’s (1999: 33) concept of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091CB9FB94E62CFBC1" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[919,1053,1084,1110]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadinae</taxonomicName>
corresponded “essentially to Cadle’s Central American group,” as supported morphologically by the hemipenial characterization provided by Myers and Cadle (1994: 27). Zaher stated that one of the three synapomorphies suggested by Myers and Cadle—distal division of the sulcus spermaticus within or at the base of the capitulum—“is nearly unique to the dipsadines, being otherwise present only in the Madagascan genus 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091D69FB5FE08AFA86" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1896" box="[583,699,1271,1297]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Geodipsas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091D69FB5FE08AFA86" box="[583,699,1271,1297]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Geodipsas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61028091F52FAF0E111FA71" blockId="14.[123,1233,1368,1745]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<superScript id="3A940443D61028091F52FAF0E2B5FAF1" attach="left" box="[124,132,1368,1382]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">9</superScript>
The “Hiss drawing” of a hemipenis labeled “ 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091D63FAF0E16AFAE7" authorityName="Guenther" authorityYear="1872" box="[589,859,1368,1392]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Hydraethiops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanogaster">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091D63FAF0E16AFAE7" box="[589,859,1368,1392]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Hydraethiops melanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” in Dowling and Duellman (“1974– 1978” [1978]: fig. 112d.4) is an accidentally transposed illustration of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091C78FADFE611FA19" baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[854,1056,1398,1422]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Natriciteres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="olivacea">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091C78FADFE611FA19" box="[854,1056,1398,1422]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Natriciteres olivacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—apparently the same hemipenis represented by the photograph of AMNH 
<quantity id="0A1904EED61028091DC6FA3BE170FA3C" box="[744,833,1427,1451]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.02641" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="in" value="11915.0">11915 in</quantity>
Zaher (1999: fig. 19, upper). The adjacent drawing (fig. 112d.5) mislabeled “ 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091D3EFA19E0B3FA5F" authorityName="Loveridge" authorityYear="1953" box="[528,642,1457,1480]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Natriciteres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091D3EFA19E0B3FA5F" box="[528,642,1457,1480]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Natriciteres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” probably is 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091C29FA18E625FA5F" authorityName="Guenther" authorityYear="1872" box="[775,1044,1456,1480]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Hydraethiops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanogaster">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091C29FA18E625FA5F" box="[775,1044,1456,1480]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Hydraethiops melanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but not the same organ illustrated under that name in Zaher (1999: fig. 18, lower).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61028091F87FA44E61BF901" blockId="14.[123,1233,1368,1745]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
N.B.: The hemipenis of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091EB1FA44E020F994" authorityName="Loveridge" authorityYear="1953" box="[415,529,1516,1539]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Natriciteres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091EB1FA44E020F994" box="[415,529,1516,1539]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Natriciteres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091D1CFA44E062F994" box="[562,595,1516,1539]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">not</emphasis>
a unilobed organ like that of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091CA2FA43E1C5F994" box="[908,1012,1515,1539]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Limnophis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091CA2FA43E1C5F994" box="[908,1012,1515,1539]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Limnophis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as implied by Zaher (1999: 32). The aforesaid illustrations of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091D03F9A1E0ACF9B7" baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[557,669,1544,1568]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Natriciteres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="olivacea">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091D03F9A1E0ACF9B7" box="[557,669,1544,1568]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">N. olivacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show what appears to be a bifurcated organ with the right lobe very incompletely everted, but, as described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61028091C5CF98EE62AF9A9" author="Bogert, Charles M." box="[882,1051,1574,1598]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="1 - 107" refId="ref15300" refString="Bogert, Charles M. 1940. Herpetological results of the Vernay Angola Expedition with notes on African reptiles in other collections. Part 1. - Snakes, including an arrangement of the African Colubridae. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 77 (1): 1 - 107 + pl. 1." type="journal article" year="1940">Bogert (1940: 33</bibRefCitation>
--35 [as 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091B5EF98FE280F9CC" authorityName="Gunther" authorityYear="1863" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" genus="Neusterophis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091B5EF98FE280F9CC" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Neusterophis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
]), the 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091FD9F9ECE358F9CC" authorityName="Loveridge" authorityYear="1953" box="[247,361,1604,1627]" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Natriciteres" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091FD9F9ECE358F9CC" box="[247,361,1604,1627]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Natriciteres</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hemipenis is only basally bifid, with one long and one very short lobe controlled by unequal-length slips of retractor muscle. Thus, the shortening leading to loss of a single lobe is one method of becoming unilobed, the alternative being distal shortening of both lobes simultaneously.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61028091F55F933E127F947" blockId="14.[123,1233,1368,1745]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<superScript id="3A940443D61028091F55F933E2BAF93E" attach="right" box="[123,139,1691,1705]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">10</superScript>
The flaplike structure shown on the left lobe in Zaher’s (1999: fig. 18) photograph of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61028091CDAF933E2F3F947" authorityName="Guenther" authorityYear="1872" class="Reptilia" family="Natricidae" genus="Hydraethiops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanogaster">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61028091CDAF933E2F3F947" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Hydraethiops melanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(AMNH 11959) is an artifact (torn tissue) of preparation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61128081F88FF49E078FD01" blockId="15.[119,1231,225,1335]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The restricted subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081EE4FF49E041FF6C" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[458,624,225,251]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae</taxonomicName>
was treated in considerable detail by Zaher (1999), who provided an exhaustive survey of xenodontine (and other) hemipenes and suggested synapomorphies for defining the clade. Owing to the lack of field-everted hemipenes, Zaher prepared and illustrated numerous hemipenes that he everted manually. Such eversions elucidate features often not interpretable from dissections of retracted organs (both kinds of data are essential for complete understanding). Limitations to manual eversion of fully retracted organs of museum specimens include (1) some necessary damage will occur to the base of the hemipenis and (2) complete 
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081EB9FE40E03AFD96" box="[407,523,488,513]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">expansion</emphasis>
often cannot be attained (resulting in a smaller circumference), even though 
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081E73FDA5E38BFDB1" box="[349,442,525,550]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">eversion</emphasis>
may be complete with all structures revealed. Both situations apply to the manually everted hemipenis of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081D68FD99E1B6FDDC" authorityName="Myers" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName=": Boulenger" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[582,903,561,587]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Amnesteophis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanauchen">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081D68FD99E1B6FDDC" box="[582,903,561,587]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Amnesteophis melanauchen</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see p. 10 and 
<figureCitation id="55DAB58ED61128081B6AFD99E6B3FDDB" box="[1092,1154,561,588]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="10.[916,959,637,658]" captionTargetBox="[119,864,230,1328]" captionTargetId="figure-126@10.[109,877,224,1336]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIG. 5. Hemipenis of Amnesteophis melanauchen (Jan 1863). Manually everted left organ of holotype of Enicognathus melanauchen, in sulcate (left), apical (top), and asulcate (right) views. (Basal half of organ is split and spread flat; the inflated distal half is fully everted but probably not maximally expanded.) The basally spinulate hemipenis is mostly spinose (spines emphasized by stippling); the spines are replaced on the small lobes by larger, soft flat- tened papillae; the unforked sulcus spermaticus extends centripetally to apex of the left lobe (sinistral sulcus) without entering a nude area in the lobular crotch; calyces are lacking (scale line = 1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5359410" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5359410/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">fig. 5</figureCitation>
). The techniques and limitations of manually everting hemipenes were discussed by Myers and Cadle (2003) and Zaher and Prudente (2003).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61128081F86FD09E1FFFAA1" blockId="15.[119,1231,225,1335]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61128081F86FD09E36DFD2B" author="Dowling, Herndon G." box="[168,348,673,700]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="320 - 328" refId="ref15919" refString="Dowling, Herndon G. 2004. On the structure of snake hemipenes with comments on their proper preparation for analysis: a reply to Cadle, Myers, Prudente, and Zaher. Herpetological Review 35 (4): 320 - 328." type="journal article" year="2004">Dowling (2004)</bibRefCitation>
seemed unenthused about the usefulness of manual eversions and responded critically to the last two papers and also to Zaher’s (1999) earlier study. Based on “prior knowledge” gained from having “prepared more than 400 ‘fresh’ hemipenes in the last half-century,” and “due to long experience and careful observation,” Dowling was able to provide imaginative explanations for hemipenial features with which he had had no experience. Two examples: he suggested (
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61128081FD4FCF4E3D5FCE1" author="Dowling, Herndon G." box="[250,484,860,886]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="320 - 328" refId="ref15919" refString="Dowling, Herndon G. 2004. On the structure of snake hemipenes with comments on their proper preparation for analysis: a reply to Cadle, Myers, Prudente, and Zaher. Herpetological Review 35 (4): 320 - 328." type="journal article" year="2004">Dowling, 2004: 321</bibRefCitation>
) that “the disappearing calyces” (the “pseudocalyces” of Myers and Cadle) on an everted 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081E8BFC29E02FFC0C" authorityName="C.W.Myers &amp; Cadle" authorityYear="1994" box="[421,542,897,923]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Psomophis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081E8BFC29E02FFC0C" box="[421,542,897,923]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Psomophis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hemipenis were “an artifact of incomplete specimen preparation” (i.e., not injecting the “outer lymph sinus”), and he predicted (ibid.: 325) how the everted hemipenes of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081E34FC64E3A7FC71" box="[282,406,972,998]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Xenopholis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081E34FC64E3A7FC71" box="[282,406,972,998]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Xenopholis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
really 
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081ECDFC64E01CFC71" box="[483,557,972,998]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">should</emphasis>
look after stating that five of Zaher’s illustrations were “so inaccurate as to place the taxa in the wrong family.” 
<superScript id="3A940443D61128081DC4FC58E0CCFB96" attach="left" box="[746,765,1008,1025]" fontSize="7" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">11</superScript>
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61128081C29FC59E607FB9B" author="Dowling, Herndon G." box="[775,1078,1009,1036]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="320 - 328" refId="ref15919" refString="Dowling, Herndon G. 2004. On the structure of snake hemipenes with comments on their proper preparation for analysis: a reply to Cadle, Myers, Prudente, and Zaher. Herpetological Review 35 (4): 320 - 328." type="journal article" year="2004">Dowling (2004: 325–327)</bibRefCitation>
particularly critiqued Zaher’s (1999) photographs of manually everted hemipenes by “doing a page-by-page survey of [Zaher’s] entire study” and listed those illustrations he judged to be based on distorted or incompletely everted organs. However, few of the supposed “incomplete” eversions or “distortions” mask the synapomorphic structures that Zaher discussed, nor was Dowling’s critique as thorough as he implied. Witness that Zaher’s study (1999: 154–156) included photographs of hemipenes of three species of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081ECAFB79E07BFB7C" box="[484,586,1233,1259]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Xenodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081ECAFB79E07BFB7C" box="[484,586,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Xenodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and yet 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD61128081D92FB79E180FB7B" author="Dowling, Herndon G." box="[700,945,1233,1260]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="320 - 328" refId="ref15919" refString="Dowling, Herndon G. 2004. On the structure of snake hemipenes with comments on their proper preparation for analysis: a reply to Cadle, Myers, Prudente, and Zaher. Herpetological Review 35 (4): 320 - 328." type="journal article" year="2004">Dowling (2004: 326)</bibRefCitation>
asserted that “it seems strange that Zaher failed to illustrate the hemipenis of the 
<typeStatus id="125A17A9D61128081C1BFB5FE156FA86" box="[821,871,1271,1297]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
genus of xenodontine snakes (
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081FAFFAB4E2D6FAA1" box="[129,231,1308,1334]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Xenodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081FAFFAB4E2D6FAA1" box="[129,231,1308,1334]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Xenodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081E2DFAB5E324FAA1" box="[259,277,1309,1334]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">v.</emphasis>
my Fig. 11 [= Dowling’s own accompanying illustration])”!
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61128081F57FAE6E140F91C" blockId="15.[121,1230,1358,1734]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<superScript id="3A940443D61128081F57FAE6E2B9FACB" attach="right" box="[121,136,1358,1372]" fontSize="6" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">11</superScript>
Concerning pseudocalyces: Normal calyces have walls of varying flexibility but do 
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081CFAFAE7E1C4FAF1" box="[980,1013,1359,1382]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">not</emphasis>
disappear no matter how the organ is everted or to what extent it is inflated. As noted by Myers and Cadle (1994: 13), retracted 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081FABFA20E2DEFA37" authorityName="C.W.Myers &amp; Cadle" authorityYear="1994" box="[133,239,1416,1440]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Psomophis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081FABFA20E2DEFA37" box="[133,239,1416,1440]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Psomophis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hemipenes have obliquely transverse folds of large spinulate papillae that are connected longitudinally by fine tissue folds, which bear striking resemblance to calyces “when the inverted lobe is incised and gently parted.” The connecting longitudinal folds, however, “can be flattened by micromanipulation with fine teasing needles.” The calyxlike structures were absent on the only available field-everted organ and were judged to have disappeared during inflation owing to stretching of the fine connecting folds (Myers and Cadle, 1994: 10–13). Two manually everted 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081D73F9B3E0F9F9A4" authorityName="C.W.Myers &amp; Cadle" authorityYear="1994" box="[605,712,1563,1587]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Psomophis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081D73F9B3E0F9F9A4" box="[605,712,1563,1587]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Psomophis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
hemipenes are fully everted but not completely expanded. The transverse papillate folds are evident in photographs (Zaher, 1999: fig. 74), but the connecting longitudinal folds show only at high magnification as hairline folds that “probably would disappear in a maximally expanded fresh eversion” (Myers and Cadle, 2003: 296, 
<figureCitation id="55DAB58ED61128081C1EF9DBE155F91C" box="[816,868,1651,1675]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[123,165,1632,1653]" captionTargetBox="[120,1224,1045,1600]" captionTargetId="figure-59@6.[120,1224,1045,1600]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 3. Enicognathus melanauchen Jan 1863. Head and neck of holotype (scale line = 5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5359406" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5359406/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD61128081F88F938E650F951" blockId="15.[121,1230,1358,1734]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
Concerning 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081E08F938E3F7F93F" authority=": The" authorityName="The" box="[294,454,1680,1704]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Xenopholis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081E08F938E3A2F93F" box="[294,403,1680,1704]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Xenopholis</emphasis>
: The
</taxonomicName>
appearance of the hemipenis of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D61128081C37F939E1B0F93F" baseAuthorityName="Wucherer" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[793,897,1680,1704]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" genus="Xenopholis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scalaris">
<emphasis id="FF957519D61128081C37F939E1B0F93F" box="[793,897,1680,1704]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">X. scalaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
illustrated by Zaher (1999: 168, fig. 95) compares favorably with one that I field-everted in 
<collectingRegion id="0F2567E9D61128081DCEF906E177F951" box="[736,838,1710,1734]" country="Brazil" name="Rondonia" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Rondônia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="B5F6E99BD61128081C7FF906E1BDF951" box="[849,908,1710,1734]" name="Brazil" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(AMNH R-130238).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F85FF49E61BFED1" blockId="16.[124,1224,225,327]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Zaher et al. (2009: 141) have reworked the classification of “ 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171C4AFF49E63DFF6C" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[868,1036,225,251]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae</taxonomicName>
,” returning it to earlier concepts of a single group of New World “xenodontines” that (because of nomenclatural priority) would now have to be called “dipsadines.” Their new groupings follow:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F55FE33E3C8FE24" blockId="16.[123,505,411,435]" box="[123,505,411,435]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Family 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171FE5FE33E3C8FE24" authority="Bonaparte, 1838" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[203,505,411,435]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadidae Bonaparte, 1838</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F85FE65E04EFE72" blockId="16.[171,639,461,485]" box="[171,639,461,485]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171E33FE65E04EFE72" authority="Zaher et al., 2009" authorityName="Zaher" authorityYear="2009" box="[285,639,461,485]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Carphophiinae">Carphophiinae Zaher et al., 2009</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F85FE57E07AFD80" blockId="16.[171,587,511,535]" box="[171,587,511,535]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171E33FE57E07AFD80" authority="Bonaparte, 1838" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[285,587,511,535]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadinae Bonaparte, 1838</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F85FD99E126FDDE" blockId="16.[171,791,561,585]" box="[171,791,561,585]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171E33FD99E05BFDDE" authority="Bonaparte, 1845" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[285,618,561,585]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae Bonaparte, 1845</taxonomicName>
(with 14 tribes)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F82FD31E133FCDF" blockId="16.[123,1231,665,1251]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171E06FD31E3FFFD24" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[296,462,665,691]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae</taxonomicName>
was now said to have “No known synapomorphies” because synapomorphies presented by Zaher (1999) were moved to family 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171C5BFD16E1CBFD4F" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[885,1018,702,728]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadidae</taxonomicName>
for complex and unresolved issues explained by Zaher et al. (2009: 140). Nonetheless, subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171B0EFD4BE6F7FD6A" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[1056,1222,739,765]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae</taxonomicName>
was retained (appropriately in my view) to avoid changing “the well-established taxonomic hierarchy for this group” (Zaher et al., 2009: 141–142).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F85FCFCE16CFBBE" blockId="16.[123,1231,665,1251]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
I have no reason to challenge the phylogeny that led to this classification except to note that ongoing DNA sampling still is insufficient for a thoroughly robust testing of these groupings (cf. Vidal et al., 2000; Kelly et al., 2003; Lawson et al., 2005: 594; 
<bibRefCitation id="A970D4FAD60E28171CB5FC36E646FC2F" author="Hedges, S. Blair" box="[923,1143,926,953]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref16407" refString="Hedges, S. Blair. 2009. Molecular phylogeny, classification, and biogeography of West Indian racer snakes of the tribe Alsophiini (Squamata, Dipsadidae, Xenodontinae). Zootaxa 2067: 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="2009">Hedges et al., 2009</bibRefCitation>
; Zaher et al., 2009). Therefore the 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171EE7FC6BE07EFC4A" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[457,591,963,989]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadinae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171DBFFC6BE108FC4A" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[657,825,963,989]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae</taxonomicName>
are retained herein for practical reasons as subfamilies of 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171E9BFC41E00BFB94" authorityName="Oppell" authorityYear="1811" box="[437,570,1001,1027]" class="Reptilia" family="Colubridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Colubridae</taxonomicName>
sensu lato for reasons discussed above (introductory paragraphs under Comparisons and Higher-Level Taxonomy).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CD5EA90BD60E28171F85FB9CE0DDFB74" blockId="16.[123,1231,665,1251]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Herndon Dowling has been a long-time proponent of assigning colubrid snake genera to tribes (e.g., see Dowling and Duellman, “1974–1978” [1978]). Zaher et al. (2009) have significantly advanced the process by distributing the colubrid subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171C8CFBD6E679FB0F" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1845" box="[930,1096,1150,1176]" class="Reptilia" family="Xenodontinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Xenodontinae</taxonomicName>
among 14 tribes, which facilitates discussion and further research. Tribal designations and molecular sampling are much less complete for the 
<taxonomicName id="0AE1D288D60E28171D4EFB61E0D9FB74" authorityName="Bonaparte" authorityYear="1838" box="[608,744,1225,1251]" class="Reptilia" family="Dipsadinae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Dipsadinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
